what is dark matter

Dark matter is a form of matter that does not emit, absorb, or reflect electromagnetic radiation, making it undetectable by conventional means. It is inferred to exist due to its gravitational effects on visible matter, radiation, and the large-scale structure of the universe. Dark matter is estimated to comprise about 27% of the universe's total mass-energy content.
